            "answer_text": "David Weinehall has written an amazing answer on the issues surrounding the themes of the books. I\u2019ll hit into the narrative: First person. Now, I don\u2019t mind a first person book - if it\u2019s written well. Unfortunately, these books are not.It\u2019s\u2026.boring. A lot of it is describing Bella\u2019s day to day routines, and they are not only repetitive, but come across as Stephanie Meyers\u2019 vanity.The Breaking Dawn battle. Oh god. The battle. WHAT BATTLE? Literally most of Breaking Dawn was dedicated to the vampires and werewolves negotiating an alliance against the Volturi with a grand plan to protect Renesmee (Who I will get to in a sec). And then, the Volturi arrive and everyone just\u2026\u2026.TALKS. They. Literally. Talk. Things. Out. It was like one giant family therapy session. And everybody survived.The Eclipse battle. Oh, wait. It was told from Bella\u2019s point of view\u2026.where she was hiding in a tent with Jacob, away from the action.The Twilight battle between Edward and James. Oh wait\u2026.Bella got knocked out so we saw nothing.Renesmee. *Vom*. Albus Severus was a better name (Harry Potter reference). The combination of the mothers\u2019 names - Renee and Esme. And Carlie for the middle name (a combination of Charlie and Carlisle). A half-human-vampire hybrid who - conveniently - will be stuck as a 15-year-old-looking girl for eternity when she reaches 7 years of age. And Nessie as a nickname? Really? At least Bella attacked Jacob for that.And while we\u2019re on the subject\u2026has nobody mentioned that Jacob who was in love with Bella is destined to be with Bella\u2019s daughter? That\u2019s\u2026that\u2019s not slightly creepy? But hey, there\u2019s like 90 years between Edward and Bella, what\u2019s like, biological 18 years between Jacob and Renesmee? *Listen up kids, it\u2019s not a sexual predator if it\u2019s attractive*. *FACEDESK*",
