            "answer_text": "OK, I admit, I have read them. While the grammar might not be up to snuff, the story telling is a bit formulaic, and some bits are pretty ridiculous, my main beef is with its not too subtle moral lessons: Stalking is perfectly fine as long as you love someoneOverprotection to the point of forbidding your girlfriend to meet other boys goes with the territorySingle men cannot be expected to learn to cook, no matter how long they remain single, but women are(A girl\u2019s) life revolves around beauty and popularityMothers should be prepared to die in pregnancy rather than have an abortion even if they know that they have no realistic option to survivePremarital sex is like the worst thing ever, ever, ever! It\u2019s a sin and will prevent you from salvation, bla bla bla.This book is basically Conservative self-loathing for women 101. All characters fall rather nicely into the gender stereotypes. Sigh. Is there something positive I can say about them? Yes. I felt that the second book represented depression in a rather interesting way, and some of the secondary characters (notably Carlisle, Alice, Jasper, and most of the Volturi) were fairly interesting. I think a book about Alice & Jasper, or about Carlisle, would\u2019ve been far more interesting. ",
