                "href": "/profile/Dina-Alia-2"
            },
            "answer_text": "Yes and no. It takes up a lot of themes that are present in classical literature, but since Meyer doesn\u2019t write particularly well it falls flat. I never had the stomach to read all of Lolita or Silence of the Lambs, nor the patience to read any of Anne Rice\u2019s novels in full, so I can\u2019t truly compare them\u2026 but if it\u2019s only okay when the writing is good, how is that different from saying abuse (in fiction) is okay as long as the abuser is attractive. Maybe it\u2019s because of my own experiences, but I don\u2019t want to criticize people\u2019s ways of expressing themselves. I think it\u2019s just as gross for people to see something sexual in an explicitly non-sexual connection. If there\u2019s anything creepy about it it\u2019s that the boy wants to be her father. Could have done without that part. Do I think Meyer wrote the books to convey how creepy the concept of soulmates is? I don\u2019t even think I care. That\u2019s what she said whether or not she meant to. ",
